[2026-03-12T15:44:25Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01RPZW5iWJqnQ1S1nSCVRrhh","type":"tool_result","content":"     1Ôćĺ# Workflows\n     2Ôćĺ\n     3ÔćĺCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4Ôćĺ\n     5Ôćĺ## Workflow Locations\n     6Ôćĺ\n     7ÔćĺCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8Ôćĺ\n     9Ôćĺ**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ÔÇö Run inside a Docker\n    10Ôćĺcontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11Ôćĺstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12Ôćĺ\n    13Ôćĺ**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ÔÇö Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14Ôćĺprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15Ôćĺdispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16Ôćĺpoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17Ôćĺ\n    18ÔćĺA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19Ôćĺuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20Ôćĺ\n    21Ôćĺ| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22Ôćĺ|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23Ôćĺ| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24Ôćĺ| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25Ôćĺ| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26Ôćĺ\n    27ÔćĺOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28Ôćĺsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29Ôćĺ\n    30ÔćĺThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31Ôćĺobject with the following fields:\n    32Ôćĺ\n    33Ôćĺ| Field | Required | Description |\n    34Ôćĺ|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35Ôćĺ| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36Ôćĺ| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37Ôćĺ| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38Ôćĺ| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39Ôćĺ| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40Ôćĺ\n    41ÔćĺThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42Ôćĺcompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43ÔćĺTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44Ôćĺreassignment.\n    45Ôćĺ\n    46ÔćĺThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47Ôćĺfile is a parse error.\n    48Ôćĺ\n    49Ôćĺ## Concepts\n    50Ôćĺ\n    51Ôćĺ| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52Ôćĺ|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53Ôćĺ| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54Ôćĺ| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55Ôćĺ| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56Ôćĺ| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57Ôćĺ| done     | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö successful completion                     |\n    58Ôćĺ| abort    | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö failure with error reporting              |\n    59Ôćĺ\n    60Ôćĺ## Step Types\n    61Ôćĺ\n    62ÔćĺStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63Ôćĺ\n    64Ôćĺ**agent** (has `prompt`) ÔÇö Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65Ôćĺto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66Ôćĺcontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67Ôćĺ\n    68Ôćĺ**script** (has `run`) ÔÇö Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69Ôćĺany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70Ôćĺ\n    71Ôćĺ**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ÔÇö Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72Ôćĺuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73Ôćĺ\n    74ÔćĺA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75Ôćĺparse error.\n    76Ôćĺ\n    77Ôćĺ## DSL Syntax\n    78Ôćĺ\n    79Ôćĺ```\n    80Ôćĺworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    81Ôćĺ  step code {\n    82Ôćĺ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    83Ôćĺ    container {\n    84Ôćĺ      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    85Ôćĺ      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    86Ôćĺ    }\n    87Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    88Ôćĺ  }\n    89Ôćĺ\n    90Ôćĺ  step check {\n    91Ôćĺ    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    92Ôćĺ    results = [pass, fail]\n    93Ôćĺ  }\n    94Ôćĺ\n    95Ôćĺ  step review {\n    96Ôćĺ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    97Ôćĺ    input = step.code.output\n    98Ôćĺ    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    99Ôćĺ  }\n   100Ôćĺ\n   101Ôćĺ  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   102Ôćĺ  code:success -> check\n   103Ôćĺ  code:fail -> abort\n   104Ôćĺ  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n   105Ôćĺ\n   106Ôćĺ  check:pass -> review\n   107Ôćĺ  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n   108Ôćĺ\n   109Ôćĺ  review:approved -> done\n   110Ôćĺ  review:changes_requested -> code\n   111Ôćĺ}\n   112Ôćĺ```\n   113Ôćĺ\n   114Ôćĺ## Key Properties\n   115Ôćĺ\n   116Ôćĺ**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   117Ôćĺfield makes it a script step.\n   118Ôćĺ\n   119Ôćĺ**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   120Ôćĺreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   121Ôćĺ\n   122Ôćĺ**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   123Ôćĺexisting ones by rewiring ÔÇö without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   124ÔćĺCloche's self-evolution feature.\n   125Ôćĺ\n   126Ôćĺ**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   127Ôćĺwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   128Ôćĺ\n   129Ôćĺ## Wire Output Mappings\n   130Ôćĺ\n   131ÔćĺWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   132Ôćĺthem as environment variables into the target step:\n   133Ôćĺ\n   134Ôćĺ```\n   135Ôćĺstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   136Ôćĺ```\n   137Ôćĺ\n   138ÔćĺThe general form:\n   139Ôćĺ\n   140Ôćĺ```\n   141ÔćĺFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   142Ôćĺ```\n   143Ôćĺ\n   144ÔćĺWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   145Ôćĺstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   146Ôćĺ\n   147Ôćĺ| Expression | Meaning |\n   148Ôćĺ|---|---|\n   149Ôćĺ| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   150Ôćĺ| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   151Ôćĺ| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   152Ôćĺ| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   153Ôćĺ| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   154Ôćĺ\n   155ÔćĺIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   156Ôćĺstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   157Ôćĺvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   158Ôćĺ\n   159ÔćĺIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   160Ôćĺreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   161Ôćĺwires to different steps without conflict.\n   162Ôćĺ\n   163Ôćĺ## The `host {}` Block\n   164Ôćĺ\n   165ÔćĺHost workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\n   166Ôćĺdefaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\n   167Ôćĺprefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n   168Ôćĺ\n   169Ôćĺ```\n   170Ôćĺworkflow \"main\" {\n   171Ôćĺ  host {\n   172Ôćĺ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   173Ôćĺ  }\n   174Ôćĺ  ...\n   175Ôćĺ}\n   176Ôćĺ```\n   177Ôćĺ\n   178ÔćĺSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   179Ôćĺ`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\n   180Ôćĺresolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\n   181Ôćĺstep-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n   182Ôćĺ`claude`.\n   183Ôćĺ\n   184Ôćĺ## Host Workflow Example\n   185Ôćĺ\n   186ÔćĺA three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   187Ôćĺworkflows:\n   188Ôćĺ\n   189Ôćĺ```\n   190Ôćĺ# .cloche/host.cloche ÔÇö runs on the host machine\n   191Ôćĺ\n   192Ôćĺworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   193Ôćĺ  step fetch-tickets {\n   194Ôćĺ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   195Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n   196Ôćĺ  }\n   197Ôćĺ\n   198Ôćĺ  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   199Ôćĺ  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   200Ôćĺ}\n   201Ôćĺ\n   202Ôćĺworkflow \"main\" {\n   203Ôćĺ  host {\n   204Ôćĺ    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   205Ôćĺ  }\n   206Ôćĺ\n   207Ôćĺ  step prepare-prompt {\n   208Ôćĺ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   209Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n   210Ôćĺ  }\n   211Ôćĺ\n   212Ôćĺ  step develop {\n   213Ôćĺ    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   214Ôćĺ    results       = [success, fail]\n   215Ôćĺ  }\n   216Ôćĺ\n   217Ôćĺ  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   218Ôćĺ  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   219Ôćĺ  develop:success        -> done\n   220Ôćĺ  develop:fail           -> done\n   221Ôćĺ}\n   222Ôćĺ\n   223Ôćĺworkflow \"finalize\" {\n   224Ôćĺ  step push-for-review {\n   225Ôćĺ    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   226Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n   227Ôćĺ  }\n   228Ôćĺ\n   229Ôćĺ  push-for-review:success -> done\n   230Ôćĺ  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   231Ôćĺ}\n   232Ôćĺ```\n   233Ôćĺ\n   234ÔćĺThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   235Ôćĺruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   236ÔćĺThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   237ÔćĺThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   238ÔćĺThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   239Ôćĺ`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   240Ôćĺ\n   241Ôćĺ## Execution Model\n   242Ôćĺ\n   243Ôćĺ**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   244Ôćĺcontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   245Ôćĺwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   246ÔćĺAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   247Ôćĺ\n   248Ôćĺ**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   249Ôćĺ`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   250Ôćĺin three phases (list-tasks Ôćĺ main Ôćĺ finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   251Ôćĺworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   252Ôćĺif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   253Ôćĺhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   254Ôćĺruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   255Ôćĺ`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   256Ôćĺpoints to the actual project directory.\n   257Ôćĺ"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"221369ce-d654-4cd4-877a-e329688c1fa8","uuid":"026118a8-7614-463c-942c-4ab83797ae4a","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) ÔÇö Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) ÔÇö Run on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\nsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject with the following fields:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\ncompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\nTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\nreassignment.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step ÔÇö failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) ÔÇö Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) ÔÇö Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) ÔÇö Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n  step code {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    container {\n      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    }\n    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n  }\n\n  step check {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [pass, fail]\n  }\n\n  step review {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    input = step.code.output\n    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n  code:success -> check\n  code:fail -> abort\n  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n\n  check:pass -> review\n  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n\n  review:approved -> done\n  review:changes_requested -> code\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring ÔÇö without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Wire Output Mappings\n\nWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\nthem as environment variables into the target step:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nThe general form:\n\n```\nFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n```\n\nWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\nstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\nstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\nvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## The `host {}` Block\n\nHost workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\ndefaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\nprefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\nresolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\nstep-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n`claude`.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\nworkflows:\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche ÔÇö runs on the host machine\n\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\nruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\nThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\nThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\nThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\nin three phases (list-tasks Ôćĺ main Ôćĺ finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\nworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\nif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\nhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\nruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\npoints to the actual project directory.\n","numLines":257,"startLine":1,"totalLines":257}}}
