[2026-03-12T15:44:25Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_019z7X9mM9hk8VXeU3gG3ga6","type":"tool_result","content":"     1Ôćĺ# Ruby Calculator\n     2Ôćĺ\n     3ÔćĺA Ruby arithmetic expression parser and evaluator, built entirely by\n     4Ôćĺ[Cloche](../../README.md) ÔÇö an autonomous workflow system for coding agents.\n     5Ôćĺ\n     6Ôćĺ## What it does\n     7Ôćĺ\n     8Ôćĺ```ruby\n     9Ôćĺcalc = Calculator.new\n    10Ôćĺcalc.evaluate(\"2 + 3 * (4 - 1)\")  # => 11.0\n    11Ôćĺcalc.evaluate(\"-(3 + 2) * 2\")     # => -10.0\n    12Ôćĺcalc.evaluate(\"3.14 * 2\")         # => 6.28\n    13Ôćĺ```\n    14Ôćĺ\n    15ÔćĺSupports `+`, `-`, `*`, `/` with correct operator precedence, parentheses,\n    16Ôćĺdecimal numbers, and negative numbers. Uses a recursive descent parser ÔÇö no\n    17Ôćĺ`eval()`.\n    18Ôćĺ\n    19Ôćĺ## How this was built\n    20Ôćĺ\n    21ÔćĺThis project was generated in a single Cloche workflow run. No human wrote any\n    22Ôćĺof the Ruby code. The command:\n    23Ôćĺ\n    24Ôćĺ```\n    25Ôćĺcloche run --workflow develop --prompt '<prompt>'\n    26Ôćĺ```\n    27Ôćĺ\n    28ÔćĺThe prompt passed to Cloche:\n    29Ôćĺ\n    30Ôćĺ> Build a Ruby calculator application that parses and evaluates arithmetic\n    31Ôćĺ> expressions from string input. Requirements:\n    32Ôćĺ>\n    33Ôćĺ> 1. A Calculator class with an evaluate(expression) method that takes a string like \"2 + 3 * (4 - 1)\" and returns the numeric result as a float\n    34Ôćĺ> 2. Support operators: +, -, *, / with correct operator precedence (* and / bind tighter than + and -)\n    35Ôćĺ> 3. Support parentheses for grouping subexpressions\n    36Ôćĺ> 4. Support integer and decimal numbers, including negative numbers like -5 or -(3+2)\n    37Ôćĺ> 5. Raise meaningful errors for: mismatched parentheses, division by zero, invalid tokens\n    38Ôćĺ> 6. Use a recursive descent parser (tokenizer -> parser -> evaluator), not eval()\n    39Ôćĺ> 7. A Gemfile listing minitest and rubocop as dependencies\n    40Ôćĺ> 8. A Rakefile with default task running tests\n    41Ôćĺ> 9. Comprehensive minitest tests covering: basic ops, precedence, nested parens, decimals, negative numbers, whitespace handling, and all error cases\n    42Ôćĺ> 10. A .rubocop.yml with reasonable defaults\n    43Ôćĺ>\n    44Ôćĺ> All source files go in lib/, tests in test/.\n    45Ôćĺ\n    46Ôćĺ## The workflow\n    47Ôćĺ\n    48ÔćĺThe `develop.cloche` workflow defines the full build-test-fix pipeline:\n    49Ôćĺ\n    50Ôćĺ```\n    51Ôćĺimplement Ôćĺ test Ôćĺ lint ÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÉ\n    52Ôćĺ                ÔööÔćĺ quality ÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöĄ collect all Ôćĺ done\n    53Ôćĺ                              Ôöé\n    54Ôćĺ           ÔöîÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇ fix ÔćÉÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöś (on any failure)\n    55Ôćĺ           ÔööÔćĺ test (retry loop, max 2 fix attempts)\n    56Ôćĺ```\n    57Ôćĺ\n    58Ôćĺ1. **implement** ÔÇö Claude Code writes all project files inside a Docker\n    59Ôćĺ   container based on the prompt\n    60Ôćĺ2. **test** ÔÇö `bundle exec rake test` runs the minitest suite\n    61Ôćĺ3. **lint** + **quality** run concurrently:\n    62Ôćĺ   - **lint** ÔÇö `bundle exec rubocop` checks style\n    63Ôćĺ   - **quality** ÔÇö [speedometer](https://github.com/your-org/speedometer)\n    64Ôćĺ     scores the git diff for code quality signals\n    65Ôćĺ4. **fix** ÔÇö if lint or quality fails, Claude Code gets the failure output and\n    66Ôćĺ   fixes the code (max 2 attempts)\n    67Ôćĺ5. After fix, the pipeline re-runs from **test**\n    68Ôćĺ\n    69Ôćĺ### Actual execution trace\n    70Ôćĺ\n    71Ôćĺ| Step | Result | Notes |\n    72Ôćĺ|------|--------|-------|\n    73Ôćĺ| implement | success | Wrote calculator, tests, Gemfile, Rakefile, .rubocop.yml |\n    74Ôćĺ| test | success | 45 tests passed on first attempt |\n    75Ôćĺ| lint | fail | rubocop found style issues |\n    76Ôćĺ| quality | success | speedometer scored the diff clean |\n    77Ôćĺ| fix | success | Claude Code fixed the lint violations |\n    78Ôćĺ| test | success | re-validated after fix |\n    79Ôćĺ| lint | success | clean on second pass |\n    80Ôćĺ| quality | success | still clean |\n    81Ôćĺ| **collect all** | **done** | ~4 minutes total |\n    82Ôćĺ\n    83Ôćĺ## Run artifacts\n    84Ôćĺ\n    85ÔćĺThe `.cloche/` directory is created at runtime and contains the full state of\n    86Ôćĺthe workflow run. It's checked in here as documentation of how the run\n    87Ôćĺprogressed.\n    88Ôćĺ\n    89Ôćĺ```\n    90Ôćĺ.cloche/\n    91Ôćĺ  prompt.txt              # The user prompt passed via --prompt\n    92Ôćĺ  output/\n    93Ôćĺ    test.log              # stdout from the test step (final pass)\n    94Ôćĺ    lint.log              # stdout from the lint step (final pass)\n    95Ôćĺ    quality.log           # stdout from the quality step\n    96Ôćĺ  attempt_count/\n    97Ôćĺ    implement             # \"1\" ÔÇö implement ran once\n    98Ôćĺ    fix                   # \"1\" ÔÇö fix ran once (lint failed, fix succeeded)\n    99Ôćĺ```\n   100Ôćĺ\n   101Ôćĺ`prompt.txt` is the input ÔÇö the user's request injected into the agent's prompt\n   102Ôćĺtemplate. The `output/*.log` files are the outputs ÔÇö captured from each script\n   103Ôćĺstep and fed back to the fix agent when something fails. `attempt_count/` tracks\n   104Ôćĺhow many times each step has been invoked, used to enforce `max_attempts` limits.\n   105Ôćĺ\n   106ÔćĺThe logs here reflect the **final successful pass** (after the fix step resolved\n   107Ôćĺthe lint issues):\n   108Ôćĺ\n   109Ôćĺ**test.log** ÔÇö 45 tests, 47 assertions, 0 failures:\n   110Ôćĺ```\n   111ÔćĺFinished in 0.002216s, 20305.9061 runs/s, 21208.3908 assertions/s.\n   112Ôćĺ45 runs, 47 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 skips\n   113Ôćĺ```\n   114Ôćĺ\n   115Ôćĺ**lint.log** ÔÇö clean:\n   116Ôćĺ```\n   117Ôćĺ4 files inspected, no offenses detected\n   118Ôćĺ```\n   119Ôćĺ\n   120Ôćĺ**quality.log** ÔÇö no diff to score (all files were new/untracked):\n   121Ôćĺ```\n   122ÔćĺNo changes to score.\n   123Ôćĺ```\n   124Ôćĺ\n   125Ôćĺ## Running locally\n   126Ôćĺ\n   127Ôćĺ```\n   128Ôćĺbundle install\n   129Ôćĺbundle exec rake test\n   130Ôćĺ```\n   131Ôćĺ"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"221369ce-d654-4cd4-877a-e329688c1fa8","uuid":"dba19c22-44bb-455a-adaa-65a17f538197","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/examples/ruby-calculator/README.md","content":"# Ruby Calculator\n\nA Ruby arithmetic expression parser and evaluator, built entirely by\n[Cloche](../../README.md) ÔÇö an autonomous workflow system for coding agents.\n\n## What it does\n\n```ruby\ncalc = Calculator.new\ncalc.evaluate(\"2 + 3 * (4 - 1)\")  # => 11.0\ncalc.evaluate(\"-(3 + 2) * 2\")     # => -10.0\ncalc.evaluate(\"3.14 * 2\")         # => 6.28\n```\n\nSupports `+`, `-`, `*`, `/` with correct operator precedence, parentheses,\ndecimal numbers, and negative numbers. Uses a recursive descent parser ÔÇö no\n`eval()`.\n\n## How this was built\n\nThis project was generated in a single Cloche workflow run. No human wrote any\nof the Ruby code. The command:\n\n```\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt '<prompt>'\n```\n\nThe prompt passed to Cloche:\n\n> Build a Ruby calculator application that parses and evaluates arithmetic\n> expressions from string input. Requirements:\n>\n> 1. A Calculator class with an evaluate(expression) method that takes a string like \"2 + 3 * (4 - 1)\" and returns the numeric result as a float\n> 2. Support operators: +, -, *, / with correct operator precedence (* and / bind tighter than + and -)\n> 3. Support parentheses for grouping subexpressions\n> 4. Support integer and decimal numbers, including negative numbers like -5 or -(3+2)\n> 5. Raise meaningful errors for: mismatched parentheses, division by zero, invalid tokens\n> 6. Use a recursive descent parser (tokenizer -> parser -> evaluator), not eval()\n> 7. A Gemfile listing minitest and rubocop as dependencies\n> 8. A Rakefile with default task running tests\n> 9. Comprehensive minitest tests covering: basic ops, precedence, nested parens, decimals, negative numbers, whitespace handling, and all error cases\n> 10. A .rubocop.yml with reasonable defaults\n>\n> All source files go in lib/, tests in test/.\n\n## The workflow\n\nThe `develop.cloche` workflow defines the full build-test-fix pipeline:\n\n```\nimplement Ôćĺ test Ôćĺ lint ÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÉ\n                ÔööÔćĺ quality ÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöĄ collect all Ôćĺ done\n                              Ôöé\n           ÔöîÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇ fix ÔćÉÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöÇÔöś (on any failure)\n           ÔööÔćĺ test (retry loop, max 2 fix attempts)\n```\n\n1. **implement** ÔÇö Claude Code writes all project files inside a Docker\n   container based on the prompt\n2. **test** ÔÇö `bundle exec rake test` runs the minitest suite\n3. **lint** + **quality** run concurrently:\n   - **lint** ÔÇö `bundle exec rubocop` checks style\n   - **quality** ÔÇö [speedometer](https://github.com/your-org/speedometer)\n     scores the git diff for code quality signals\n4. **fix** ÔÇö if lint or quality fails, Claude Code gets the failure output and\n   fixes the code (max 2 attempts)\n5. After fix, the pipeline re-runs from **test**\n\n### Actual execution trace\n\n| Step | Result | Notes |\n|------|--------|-------|\n| implement | success | Wrote calculator, tests, Gemfile, Rakefile, .rubocop.yml |\n| test | success | 45 tests passed on first attempt |\n| lint | fail | rubocop found style issues |\n| quality | success | speedometer scored the diff clean |\n| fix | success | Claude Code fixed the lint violations |\n| test | success | re-validated after fix |\n| lint | success | clean on second pass |\n| quality | success | still clean |\n| **collect all** | **done** | ~4 minutes total |\n\n## Run artifacts\n\nThe `.cloche/` directory is created at runtime and contains the full state of\nthe workflow run. It's checked in here as documentation of how the run\nprogressed.\n\n```\n.cloche/\n  prompt.txt              # The user prompt passed via --prompt\n  output/\n    test.log              # stdout from the test step (final pass)\n    lint.log              # stdout from the lint step (final pass)\n    quality.log           # stdout from the quality step\n  attempt_count/\n    implement             # \"1\" ÔÇö implement ran once\n    fix                   # \"1\" ÔÇö fix ran once (lint failed, fix succeeded)\n```\n\n`prompt.txt` is the input ÔÇö the user's request injected into the agent's prompt\ntemplate. The `output/*.log` files are the outputs ÔÇö captured from each script\nstep and fed back to the fix agent when something fails. `attempt_count/` tracks\nhow many times each step has been invoked, used to enforce `max_attempts` limits.\n\nThe logs here reflect the **final successful pass** (after the fix step resolved\nthe lint issues):\n\n**test.log** ÔÇö 45 tests, 47 assertions, 0 failures:\n```\nFinished in 0.002216s, 20305.9061 runs/s, 21208.3908 assertions/s.\n45 runs, 47 assertions, 0 failures, 0 errors, 0 skips\n```\n\n**lint.log** ÔÇö clean:\n```\n4 files inspected, no offenses detected\n```\n\n**quality.log** ÔÇö no diff to score (all files were new/untracked):\n```\nNo changes to score.\n```\n\n## Running locally\n\n```\nbundle install\nbundle exec rake test\n```\n","numLines":131,"startLine":1,"totalLines":131}}}
