[2026-03-12T15:44:25Z] [llm] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_0166dNL72T3ioPWDdynfnamS","type":"tool_result","content":"     1Ôćĺ# CLOCHE\n     2Ôćĺ\n     3ÔćĺA system for grow-coding high quality applications.\n     4Ôćĺ\n     5Ôćĺ# What is it\n     6Ôćĺ\n     7ÔćĺCloche provides \n     8Ôćĺ- containerized environments for coding agents to operate in isolation\n     9Ôćĺ- a workflow syntax for linking Agentic and Script-driven task nodes\n    10Ôćĺ- a focus on creating validated code\n    11Ôćĺ- self-evolving tooling that grows with your codebase in response to encountered errors\n    12Ôćĺ\n    13Ôćĺ## Installation\n    14Ôćĺ\n    15ÔćĺSee [docs/INSTALL.md](docs/INSTALL.md) for full installation instructions\n    16Ôćĺcovering build from source, `go install`, and other methods.\n    17Ôćĺ\n    18ÔćĺQuick version:\n    19Ôćĺ\n    20Ôćĺ```\n    21Ôćĺgit clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\n    22Ôćĺcd cloche\n    23Ôćĺmake install\n    24Ôćĺ```\n    25Ôćĺ\n    26ÔćĺThis builds all binaries, builds the Docker image, installs to `~/.local/bin/`,\n    27Ôćĺand starts the daemon. Prerequisites: Go 1.25+, Docker, Git, and an\n    28Ôćĺ`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` for agent steps.\n    29Ôćĺ\n    30Ôćĺ## Getting Started\n    31Ôćĺ\n    32Ôćĺ### 1. Initialize your project\n    33Ôćĺ\n    34ÔćĺFrom your project's git repository:\n    35Ôćĺ\n    36Ôćĺ```\n    37Ôćĺcloche init\n    38Ôćĺ```\n    39Ôćĺ\n    40ÔćĺThis scaffolds a `.cloche/` directory with a default `develop` workflow,\n    41ÔćĺDockerfile, prompt templates, host workflow, and configuration. All generated\n    42Ôćĺfiles are safe to customize.\n    43Ôćĺ\n    44ÔćĺTo use a different workflow name or base image:\n    45Ôćĺ\n    46Ôćĺ```\n    47Ôćĺcloche init --workflow my-workflow --base-image ubuntu:24.04\n    48Ôćĺ```\n    49Ôćĺ\n    50Ôćĺ### 2. Configure the Dockerfile\n    51Ôćĺ\n    52ÔćĺEdit `.cloche/Dockerfile` to install your project's build dependencies. The\n    53Ôćĺgenerated Dockerfile uses `cloche-base:latest` (which includes `cloche-agent`\n    54Ôćĺand `git`). Add your language runtime, package manager, and any tools your\n    55Ôćĺbuild and test steps need:\n    56Ôćĺ\n    57Ôćĺ```dockerfile\n    58ÔćĺFROM cloche-base:latest\n    59ÔćĺRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y ruby bundler\n    60ÔćĺCOPY . /workspace/\n    61ÔćĺRUN cd /workspace && bundle install\n    62Ôćĺ```\n    63Ôćĺ\n    64ÔćĺThe container image must have `cloche-agent` at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`,\n    65Ôćĺ`git`, an `agent` user, and `/workspace` as the working directory. See\n    66Ôćĺ[docs/USAGE.md](docs/USAGE.md#dockerfile-requirements) for full requirements.\n    67Ôćĺ\n    68Ôćĺ### 3. Define your workflow\n    69Ôćĺ\n    70ÔćĺWorkflows live in `.cloche/*.cloche` files using the Cloche DSL. A workflow is\n    71Ôćĺa directed graph of steps connected by result wiring. Steps are either agent\n    72Ôćĺprompts or shell commands:\n    73Ôćĺ\n    74Ôćĺ```\n    75Ôćĺworkflow \"develop\" {\n    76Ôćĺ  step implement {\n    77Ôćĺ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    78Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n    79Ôćĺ  }\n    80Ôćĺ\n    81Ôćĺ  step test {\n    82Ôćĺ    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    83Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail]\n    84Ôćĺ  }\n    85Ôćĺ\n    86Ôćĺ  step fix {\n    87Ôćĺ    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    88Ôćĺ    feedback = \"true\"\n    89Ôćĺ    max_attempts = \"2\"\n    90Ôćĺ    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n    91Ôćĺ  }\n    92Ôćĺ\n    93Ôćĺ  implement:success -> test\n    94Ôćĺ  implement:fail    -> abort\n    95Ôćĺ  test:success      -> done\n    96Ôćĺ  test:fail         -> fix\n    97Ôćĺ  fix:success       -> test\n    98Ôćĺ  fix:fail          -> abort\n    99Ôćĺ  fix:give-up       -> abort\n   100Ôćĺ}\n   101Ôćĺ```\n   102Ôćĺ\n   103ÔćĺEdit the prompt templates in `.cloche/prompts/` to describe the work your agent\n   104Ôćĺshould do. The `file()` function reads prompt content at execution time.\n   105Ôćĺ\n   106ÔćĺSee [docs/workflows.md](docs/workflows.md) for the full DSL reference including\n   107Ôćĺparallel branches, collect/join, wire output mappings, host workflows, and\n   108Ôćĺcontainer configuration.\n   109Ôćĺ\n   110Ôćĺ### 4. Run a workflow\n   111Ôćĺ\n   112Ôćĺ```\n   113Ôćĺcloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add a login page with email/password auth\"\n   114Ôćĺ```\n   115Ôćĺ\n   116ÔćĺCloche copies your project into a Docker container, runs the workflow steps, and\n   117Ôćĺextracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` git branch. Monitor progress with:\n   118Ôćĺ\n   119Ôćĺ```\n   120Ôćĺcloche status <run-id>\n   121Ôćĺcloche logs <run-id> -f\n   122Ôćĺ```\n   123Ôćĺ\n   124Ôćĺ### Let your LLM do the setup\n   125Ôćĺ\n   126ÔćĺYour LLM client of choice (Claude Code, Cursor, etc.) can likely handle the\n   127Ôćĺfull setup for you. Point it at this README and ask it to initialize Cloche for\n   128Ôćĺyour project ÔÇö it can run `cloche init`, tailor the Dockerfile to your stack,\n   129Ôćĺwrite prompt templates, and wire up a workflow suited to your build and test\n   130Ôćĺpipeline.\n   131Ôćĺ\n   132Ôćĺ### Further reading\n   133Ôćĺ\n   134Ôćĺ- [docs/INSTALL.md](docs/INSTALL.md) ÔÇö full installation options\n   135Ôćĺ- [docs/USAGE.md](docs/USAGE.md) ÔÇö CLI reference, project layout, configuration\n   136Ôćĺ- [docs/workflows.md](docs/workflows.md) ÔÇö workflow DSL syntax and semantics\n   137Ôćĺ- [examples/ruby-calculator/](examples/ruby-calculator/) ÔÇö a complete project built by Cloche\n   138Ôćĺ\n   139Ôćĺ## Containers\n   140Ôćĺ\n   141ÔćĺCoding agents are powerful, but running them interactively turns the human into the bottleneck.\n   142Ôćĺ\n   143ÔćĺOn the otherhand, running them in \"yolo\" mode is wildly risky.\n   144Ôćĺ\n   145ÔćĺTo allow our agents to run in a balance of safety and speed, we must disrupt the Lethal Trifecta.\n   146Ôćĺ\n   147ÔćĺFirstly, we remove their access to the full filesystem - the docker containers have access only to their\n   148Ôćĺown filespace - only copies are used - no file mounts. Environment variables are only those provided by the host\n   149Ôćĺto the container. \n   150Ôćĺ\n   151ÔćĺSecond, network access is limited to allowlists to ensure your agents can have e.g. free access to library documentation or your\n   152Ôćĺinternal documentation, but not the internet at large!\n   153Ôćĺ\n   154Ôćĺ\n   155Ôćĺ## Workflows\n   156Ôćĺ\n   157Ôćĺsee our [Workflows](docs/workflows.md) documentation!\n   158Ôćĺ\n   159Ôćĺ## Validated code\n   160Ôćĺ\n   161ÔćĺYour agents are fast, but that speed shouldn't come at the cost of quality.\n   162Ôćĺ\n   163ÔćĺKeep your validation checks in the loop with your coding agent - go beyond unit tests!\n   164Ôćĺ- validate complexity measurements\n   165Ôćĺ- automated code review\n   166Ôćĺ- auto-split large commits into stacked branches, individually reviewed and validated to keep commits simple and clean\n   167Ôćĺ- custom script and agent support to add your own checks to the mix\n   168Ôćĺ- failures are tracked and classified for use in autogenerating future validation checks\n   169Ôćĺ- validation failure feedback triggers retries to automatically resolve issues before they reach CI\n   170Ôćĺ"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"221369ce-d654-4cd4-877a-e329688c1fa8","uuid":"4dc9c03f-310b-4170-bf89-cd6d85fcaa4f","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/README.md","content":"# CLOCHE\n\nA system for grow-coding high quality applications.\n\n# What is it\n\nCloche provides \n- containerized environments for coding agents to operate in isolation\n- a workflow syntax for linking Agentic and Script-driven task nodes\n- a focus on creating validated code\n- self-evolving tooling that grows with your codebase in response to encountered errors\n\n## Installation\n\nSee [docs/INSTALL.md](docs/INSTALL.md) for full installation instructions\ncovering build from source, `go install`, and other methods.\n\nQuick version:\n\n```\ngit clone https://github.com/cloche-dev/cloche.git\ncd cloche\nmake install\n```\n\nThis builds all binaries, builds the Docker image, installs to `~/.local/bin/`,\nand starts the daemon. Prerequisites: Go 1.25+, Docker, Git, and an\n`ANTHROPIC_API_KEY` for agent steps.\n\n## Getting Started\n\n### 1. Initialize your project\n\nFrom your project's git repository:\n\n```\ncloche init\n```\n\nThis scaffolds a `.cloche/` directory with a default `develop` workflow,\nDockerfile, prompt templates, host workflow, and configuration. All generated\nfiles are safe to customize.\n\nTo use a different workflow name or base image:\n\n```\ncloche init --workflow my-workflow --base-image ubuntu:24.04\n```\n\n### 2. Configure the Dockerfile\n\nEdit `.cloche/Dockerfile` to install your project's build dependencies. The\ngenerated Dockerfile uses `cloche-base:latest` (which includes `cloche-agent`\nand `git`). Add your language runtime, package manager, and any tools your\nbuild and test steps need:\n\n```dockerfile\nFROM cloche-base:latest\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y ruby bundler\nCOPY . /workspace/\nRUN cd /workspace && bundle install\n```\n\nThe container image must have `cloche-agent` at `/usr/local/bin/cloche-agent`,\n`git`, an `agent` user, and `/workspace` as the working directory. See\n[docs/USAGE.md](docs/USAGE.md#dockerfile-requirements) for full requirements.\n\n### 3. Define your workflow\n\nWorkflows live in `.cloche/*.cloche` files using the Cloche DSL. A workflow is\na directed graph of steps connected by result wiring. Steps are either agent\nprompts or shell commands:\n\n```\nworkflow \"develop\" {\n  step implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step test {\n    run = \"make test 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    feedback = \"true\"\n    max_attempts = \"2\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n  }\n\n  implement:success -> test\n  implement:fail    -> abort\n  test:success      -> done\n  test:fail         -> fix\n  fix:success       -> test\n  fix:fail          -> abort\n  fix:give-up       -> abort\n}\n```\n\nEdit the prompt templates in `.cloche/prompts/` to describe the work your agent\nshould do. The `file()` function reads prompt content at execution time.\n\nSee [docs/workflows.md](docs/workflows.md) for the full DSL reference including\nparallel branches, collect/join, wire output mappings, host workflows, and\ncontainer configuration.\n\n### 4. Run a workflow\n\n```\ncloche run --workflow develop --prompt \"Add a login page with email/password auth\"\n```\n\nCloche copies your project into a Docker container, runs the workflow steps, and\nextracts results to a `cloche/<run-id>` git branch. Monitor progress with:\n\n```\ncloche status <run-id>\ncloche logs <run-id> -f\n```\n\n### Let your LLM do the setup\n\nYour LLM client of choice (Claude Code, Cursor, etc.) can likely handle the\nfull setup for you. Point it at this README and ask it to initialize Cloche for\nyour project ÔÇö it can run `cloche init`, tailor the Dockerfile to your stack,\nwrite prompt templates, and wire up a workflow suited to your build and test\npipeline.\n\n### Further reading\n\n- [docs/INSTALL.md](docs/INSTALL.md) ÔÇö full installation options\n- [docs/USAGE.md](docs/USAGE.md) ÔÇö CLI reference, project layout, configuration\n- [docs/workflows.md](docs/workflows.md) ÔÇö workflow DSL syntax and semantics\n- [examples/ruby-calculator/](examples/ruby-calculator/) ÔÇö a complete project built by Cloche\n\n## Containers\n\nCoding agents are powerful, but running them interactively turns the human into the bottleneck.\n\nOn the otherhand, running them in \"yolo\" mode is wildly risky.\n\nTo allow our agents to run in a balance of safety and speed, we must disrupt the Lethal Trifecta.\n\nFirstly, we remove their access to the full filesystem - the docker containers have access only to their\nown filespace - only copies are used - no file mounts. Environment variables are only those provided by the host\nto the container. \n\nSecond, network access is limited to allowlists to ensure your agents can have e.g. free access to library documentation or your\ninternal documentation, but not the internet at large!\n\n\n## Workflows\n\nsee our [Workflows](docs/workflows.md) documentation!\n\n## Validated code\n\nYour agents are fast, but that speed shouldn't come at the cost of quality.\n\nKeep your validation checks in the loop with your coding agent - go beyond unit tests!\n- validate complexity measurements\n- automated code review\n- auto-split large commits into stacked branches, individually reviewed and validated to keep commits simple and clean\n- custom script and agent support to add your own checks to the mix\n- failures are tracked and classified for use in autogenerating future validation checks\n- validation failure feedback triggers retries to automatically resolve issues before they reach CI\n","numLines":170,"startLine":1,"totalLines":170}}}
